				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tistical property</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For the comp=
uter programming concept, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stan=
dard_error_stream" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Standard error stream">st=
andard error stream</a>.</div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Standard_deviation_diagram.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Standard_devi=
ation_diagram.svg/330px-Standard_deviation_diagram.svg.png" decoding=3D"asy=
nc" width=3D"325" height=3D"163" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"400" data-file-height=3D"200"></a><figcaption>For a value that is sampl=
ed with an unbiased <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distrib=
ution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normally distributed</a> error, the ab=
ove depicts the proportion of samples that would fall between 0, 1, 2, and =
3 standard deviations above and below the actual value.</figcaption></figur=
e>
<p>The <b>standard error</b> (<b>SE</b>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_1-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error#cite=
_note-:0-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statis=
tic" title=3D"Statistic">statistic</a> (usually an <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Estimator" title=3D"Estimator">estimator</a> of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_parameter" title=3D"Statistic=
al parameter">parameter</a>, like the average or mean) is the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" title=3D"Standard deviation=
">standard deviation</a> of its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sa=
mpling_distribution" title=3D"Sampling distribution">sampling distribution<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Standard_error#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_1=
-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_e=
rror#cite_note-:0-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The standard error is often used in calcula=
tions of  <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" tit=
le=3D"Confidence interval">confidence intervals</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error=
#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_distribution" =
title=3D"Sampling distribution">sampling distribution</a> of a mean is gene=
rated by repeated sampling from the same population and recording the sampl=
e mean per sample. This forms a distribution of different sample means, and=
 this distribution has its own <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mea=
n" title=3D"Mean">mean</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Var=
iance" title=3D"Variance">variance</a>. Mathematically, the variance of the=
 sampling mean distribution obtained is equal to the variance of the popula=
tion divided by the sample size. This is because as the sample size increas=
es, sample means cluster more closely around the population mean.
</p><p>Therefore, the relationship between the standard error of the mean a=
nd the standard deviation is such that, for a given sample size, the standa=
rd error of the mean equals the standard deviation divided by the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_root" title=3D"Square root">square=
 root</a> of the sample size.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_1-2" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error#cite_note-:0-1"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> In other words, the standard error of the mean is a measure of th=
e dispersion of sample means around the population mean.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_analysis" tit=
le=3D"Regression analysis">regression analysis</a>, the term "standard erro=
r" refers either to the square root of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Reduced_chi-squared_statistic" title=3D"Reduced chi-squared statis=
tic">reduced chi-squared statistic</a> or the standard error for a particul=
ar regression coefficient (as used in, say, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">confidence int=
ervals</a>).
</p>
