<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Accuracy_of_the_estimator">=
Accuracy of the estimator</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DStandard_error&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Accuracy of the estimator"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When the sample size is small, using the standard deviation of the sampl=
e instead of the true standard deviation of the population will tend to sys=
tematically underestimate the population standard deviation, and therefore =
also the standard error. With <i>n</i> =3D 2, the underestimate is about 25=
%, but for <i>n</i> =3D 6, the underestimate is only 5%. Gurland and Tripat=
hi (1971) provide a correction and equation for this effect.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standa=
rd_error#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sokal and Rohlf (1981) give an equation of=
 the correction factor for small samples of <i>n</i> &lt; 20.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stand=
ard_error#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Unbiased_estimation_of_standard_deviation" title=3D"Unbiased estimation=
 of standard deviation">unbiased estimation of standard deviation</a> for f=
urther discussion.
</p>
