<p>In particular, the standard error of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Sample_statistic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample statistic">=
sample statistic</a> (such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samp=
le_mean" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample mean">sample mean</a>) is th=
e actual or estimated standard deviation of the sample mean in the process =
by which it was generated. In other words, it is the actual or estimated st=
andard deviation of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_d=
istribution" title=3D"Sampling distribution">sampling distribution</a> of t=
he sample statistic. The notation for standard error can be any one of SE, =
SEM (for standard error of <i>measurement</i> or <i>mean</i>), or S<sub>E</=
sub>.
</p><p>Standard errors provide simple measures of uncertainty in a value an=
d are often used because:<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fac=
t" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span tit=
le=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2025)">ci=
tation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<ul><li>in many cases, if the standard error of several individual quantiti=
es is known then the standard error of some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function=
</a> of the quantities can be easily calculated;</li>
<li>when the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribut=
ion" title=3D"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a> of the=
 value is known, it can be used to calculate an exact <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">conf=
idence interval</a>;</li>
<li>when the probability distribution is unknown, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Chebyshev%27s_inequality" title=3D"Chebyshev's inequality">=
Chebyshev</a>'s or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vysochanski=
%C3%AF%E2%80%93Petunin_inequality" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vysochans=
ki=C3=AF=E2=80=93Petunin inequality">Vysochanski=C3=AF=E2=80=93Petunin ineq=
ualities</a> can be used to calculate a conservative confidence interval; a=
nd</li>
<li>as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_size" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Sample size">sample size</a> tends to infinity the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Centr=
al limit theorem">central limit theorem</a> guarantees that the sampling di=
stribution of the mean is asymptotically <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal</a>.</li><=
/ul>
