us_standard_deviation">Standard error of mean versus standard deviation</h3=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</s=
pan><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_error&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Standard error of=
 mean versus standard deviation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In scientific and technical literature, experimental data are often summ=
arized either using the mean and standard deviation of the sample data or t=
he mean with the standard error. This often leads to confusion about their =
interchangeability. However, the mean and standard deviation are <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descriptive_statistics" title=3D"Descriptive=
 statistics">descriptive statistics</a>, whereas the standard error of the =
mean is descriptive of the random sampling process. The standard deviation =
of the sample data is a description of the variation in measurements, while=
 the standard error of the mean is a probabilistic statement about how the =
sample size will provide a better bound on estimates of the population mean=
, in light of the central limit theorem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error#cite_note-8=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>Put simply, the <b>standard error</b> of the sample mean is an estim=
ate of how far the sample mean is likely to be from the population mean, wh=
ereas the <b>standard deviation</b> of the sample is the degree to which in=
dividuals within the sample differ from the sample mean.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_e=
rror#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If the population standard deviation is finite=
, the standard error of the mean of the sample will tend to zero with incre=
asing sample size, because the estimate of the population mean will improve=
, while the standard deviation of the sample will tend to approximate the p=
opulation standard deviation as the sample size increases.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extensions">Extensions</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_error&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Extensions"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Finite_population_correctio=
n_(FPC)"><span id=3D"Finite_population_correction_.28FPC.29"></span>Finite =
population correction (FPC)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DStandard_error&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=
=3D"Edit section: Finite population correction (FPC)"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The formula given above for the standard error assumes that the populati=
on is infinite. Nonetheless, it is often used for finite populations when p=
eople are interested in measuring the process that created the existing fin=
ite population (this is called an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Analytic_and_enumerative_statistical_studies" title=3D"Analytic and enumera=
tive statistical studies">analytic study</a>). Though the above formula is =
not exactly correct when the population is finite, the difference between t=
he finite- and infinite-population versions will be small when <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_fraction" title=3D"Sampling fraction"=
>sampling fraction</a> is small (e.g. a small proportion of a finite popula=
tion is studied). In this case people often do not correct for the finite p=
opulation, essentially treating it as an "approximately infinite" populatio=
n.
</p><p>If one is interested in measuring an existing finite population that=
 will not change over time, then it is necessary to adjust for the populati=
on size (called an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_and_en=
umerative_statistical_studies" title=3D"Analytic and enumerative statistica=
l studies">enumerative study</a>). When the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sampling_fraction" title=3D"Sampling fraction">sampling fraction<=
/a> (often termed <i>f</i>) is large (approximately at 5% or more) in an <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_and_enumerative_statistical=
_studies" title=3D"Analytic and enumerative statistical studies">enumerativ=
e study</a>, the estimate of the standard error must be corrected by multip=
lying by a ''finite population correction'' (a.k.a.: <b>FPC</b>):<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Standard_error#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Standard_error#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \operatorname {FPC} =3D{\sqrt {\frac {N-n}{N-1}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>FPC</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mfrac>
              <mrow>
                <mi>N</mi>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mi>n</mi>
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                <mi>N</mi>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
            </mfrac>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \operatorname=
 {FPC} =3D{\sqrt {\frac {N-n}{N-1}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9da7bcdbcf4dd49fa27a96f24d939d9a6b0f6362" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.505ex; width:17.336ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
operatorname {FPC} =3D{\sqrt {\frac {N-n}{N-1}}}}"></span>
which, for large <i>N</i>:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \operatorname {FPC} \approx {\sqrt {1-{\frac {n}{N}}}}=3D{\sqrt=
 {1-f}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>FPC</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=88<!-- =E2=89=88 --></mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mfrac>
                <mi>n</mi>
                <mi>N</mi>
              </mfrac>
            </mrow>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mi>f</mi>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \operatorname=
 {FPC} \approx {\sqrt {1-{\frac {n}{N}}}}=3D{\sqrt {1-f}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9abeb56edc3c728361139399181b025d9d4fc29b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.671ex; width:27.807ex; height:6.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
operatorname {FPC} \approx {\sqrt {1-{\frac {n}{N}}}}=3D{\sqrt {1-f}}}"></s=
pan>
to account for the added precision gained by sampling close to a larger per=
centage of the population. The effect of the FPC is that the error becomes =
zero when the sample size <i>n</i> is equal to the population size <i>N</i>=
.
</p><p>This happens in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Survey_meth=
odology" title=3D"Survey methodology">survey methodology</a> when sampling =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_(statistics)#Replacement_=
of_selected_units" title=3D"Sampling (statistics)">without replacement</a>.=
 If sampling with replacement, then FPC does not come into play.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Correction_for_correlation_=
in_the_sample">Correction for correlation in the sample</h3><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStandard_error&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Correction for correlation in th=
e sample"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SampleBiasCoefficient.png" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thum=
b/b/b4/SampleBiasCoefficient.png/330px-SampleBiasCoefficient.png" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"310" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"360" data-file-height=3D"372"></a><figcaption>Expected error in t=
he mean of <i>A</i> for a sample of <i>n</i> data points with sample bias c=
oefficient&nbsp;<i>=CF=81</i>. The unbiased <b>standard error</b> plots as =
the <i>=CF=81</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0 diagonal line with log-log slope&nbsp;=E2=
=88=92<span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=
=3D"den">2</span></span>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>If values of the measured quantity <i>A</i> are not statistically indepe=
ndent but have been obtained from known locations in parameter space&nbsp;<=
b>x</b>, an unbiased estimate of the true standard error of the mean (actua=
lly a correction on the standard deviation part) may be obtained by multipl=
ying the calculated standard error of the sample by the factor&nbsp;<i>f</i=
>:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle f=3D{\sqrt {\frac {1+\rho }{1-\rho }}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mfrac>
              <mrow>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mi>=CF=81<!-- =CF=81 --></mi>
              </mrow>
              <mrow>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mi>=CF=81<!-- =CF=81 --></mi>
              </mrow>
            </mfrac>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle f=3D{\sqrt {\=
frac {1+\rho }{1-\rho }}},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9692608957c2ee9780d279e11a054bd33f9c3f7e" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -3.171ex; width:13.389ex; height:7.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle f=
=3D{\sqrt {\frac {1+\rho }{1-\rho }}},}"></span>
where the sample bias coefficient =CF=81 is the widely used <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prais%E2%80%93Winsten_estimation" title=3D"Prais=
=E2=80=93Winsten estimation">Prais=E2=80=93Winsten estimate</a> of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autocorrelation" title=3D"Autocorrelat=
ion">autocorrelation</a>-coefficient (a quantity between =E2=88=921 and +1)=
 for all sample point pairs. This approximate formula is for moderate to la=
rge sample sizes; the reference gives the exact formulas for any sample siz=
e, and can be applied to heavily autocorrelated time series like Wall Stree=
t stock quotes. Moreover, this formula works for positive and negative =CF=
=81 alike.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> See also <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unbiased_estimation_of_standard_deviati=
on" title=3D"Unbiased estimation of standard deviation">unbiased estimation=
 of standard deviation</a> for more discussion.
</p>
